{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01NiXMhKYZqDtPjTNY3X8jUo","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t/**\n2\t * Public TypeScript types for the OAuth2 / OpenID Connect subsystem.\n3\t *\n4\t * These types describe the *shape* of authentication data at runtime. They\n5\t * are intentionally decoupled from any specific OIDC client library so that\n6\t * the Pinia store, router guard, and UI layer only depend on the types\n7\t * declared here.\n8\t */\n9\t\n10\timport { ROLE_ADMIN, ROLE_VIEWER } from './constants'\n11\t\n12\t/**\n13\t * Canonical role assigned to an authenticated user.\n14\t *\n15\t * The dashboard recognises exactly two roles:\n16\t * - `viewer` — read-only access.\n17\t * - `admin` — full create / read / update / delete access.\n18\t *\n19\t * Providers are free to use any role names internally; the role mapping\n20\t * configured per provider translates them to these canonical values.\n21\t */\n22\texport type Role = typeof ROLE_VIEWER | typeof ROLE_ADMIN\n23\t\n24\t/**\n25\t * Mapping from provider-specific role strings to the canonical dashboard\n26\t * roles. For example, a Keycloak realm that exposes `\"dashboard-writer\"`\n27\t * can map it to `\"admin\"` with `{ \"dashboard-writer\": \"admin\" }`.\n28\t *\n29\t * When an incoming role is missing from the map, the user falls back to\n30\t * the `viewer` role so that the dashboard fails closed on privilege.\n31\t */\n32\texport type RoleMapping = Readonly<Record<string, Role>>\n33\t\n34\t/**\n35\t * Static configuration for a single OAuth2 / OpenID Connect provider.\n36\t *\n37\t * All URL-shaped fields are expected to be absolute URLs; the loader does\n38\t * not perform schema validation beyond basic type checking — operators are\n39\t * responsible for supplying correct values.\n40\t */\n41\texport interface OAuthProviderConfig {\n42\t  /**\n43\t   * Stable identifier used in callback URLs and `sessionStorage` keys.\n44\t   * Must be URL-safe (`[a-zA-Z0-9_-]+`